ted with child labour in the factory workplace. The result is a more nuanced picture of child health and child labour during the classic 'factory age' which raises important questions about the enduring stereotype of the health-impaired and abused industrial child. Peter Kirby is Professor of Social History and Director of the Centre for the Social History of Health and Healthcare at Glasgow Caledonian University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChild laborzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aChildrenxHealth and hygienezGreat BritainxHistory. 0aIndustrial hygienezGreat BritainxHistory. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh  a1780-1850.  aBritain.  aChild Labor.  aChild Workers.  aFactory Workplace.  aIndustrial Health.  aIndustrial Revolution.  aOccupational Health.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204401740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782044017423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782044017/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles